The Familiarity of New Anti-Semitism
Why do so many Holocaust survivors sense emerging threats to Judaism before they become widely visible?
Because they know that seemingly "innocent" hints can turn into accusations and eventually lead to discrimination that is then enshrined in law.
Then hysteria sets in at this point.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what's at stake.
Thus, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we too may survive.
Since the first round of the French presidential elections, it is clear that we have every reason to listen.
But not only demagogues like Jean Marie Le Pen or other unsavory right-wing extremists in Europe cause problems.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" often became foot soldiers of fascism or communism without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we are dealing with people – members of the "educated class" associated with mass media, politics, government, and universities – who condemn Israel using a language that often echoes that of the opportunists behind these anti-democratic movements.
This is not yet the majority opinion in the Western world – fortunately not yet – but it is the voice of a powerful and influential minority.
Here, the example of the French ambassador to the UK should be mentioned: recently, he referred to Israel during a dinner party in London as "this shit little country."
His vulgar language is not particularly alarming.
What is concerning, however, are the reactions to it.
Neither was he recalled by his government, nor did the Blair government call for his recall. In public, the matter was dismissed as more of a scandal.
The French press portrayed the ambassador as a victim of British low-level propaganda rather than acknowledging his own despicable attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador in Great Britain has several allies among Europe's elites.
However, Ambassador Bernard served us a valuable lesson: Through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Jewish resentments are.
As one columnist put it so aptly: Israel has become a hate object whose name one dares not utter.
We however must not only dare to speak it, we are even obliged to express it.
Given the daily attacks against Jews and synagogues in France, we must not remain silent.
It is shameful for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without worrying about their safety.
Anti-Semitic attacks are reported elsewhere too. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent that denial of the Holocaust is becoming commonplace. We must also not remain silent about the comparisons that anti-Semites and anti-Zionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While in a Palestinian television show, Israeli soldiers are portrayed as rapists and cold-blooded murderers, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we "must confront the new Nazi plague that is arising in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. People hate them almost everywhere."
During the live broadcast of a Friday prayer on Palestinian television, the preacher called on Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. No matter where you are, kill them and these Americans who are just like them."
What we should think about concerning antisemitism is that it always begins with the Jews but never ends with the Jews.
If anti-Judaism is not brought under control, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore the task of Jews as much as it is of non-Jews.
Currently, the points of attack in this struggle are clearer than ever before, as one striking aspect of today's antisemitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of antisemitism remains the same - namely, to attack the Jews - it nevertheless changes its appearance, its strategy, its rationalizations, and even its vocabulary.
Once upon a time, the Jewish religion was the target.
When that did not succeed, the Jews were expelled or killed.
When racial theory captured people's imagination in the 19th century, Jews were attacked because they belonged to a supposedly evil race.
With the existence of the State of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, today Zionism is slandered as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with antisemitism.
Just as with other nations, it is entirely legitimate to be critical of certain political strategies and decisions made by Israel.
However, antizionism is becoming increasingly similar to antisemitism.
Antizionists sometimes claim that they are not against the Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I am only against the existence of Great Britain, but I am not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
You would not believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people but hate their state.
And yet, there are people associated with Israel who claim to be able to do exactly that.
In various UN organizations, insults directed at Israel are on the agenda.
This demonization of the only democratic state in the Middle East is a key point of this new antisemitism.
When Israel is described as "the enemy of everything good and the source of all evil," then within the UN, the "doctrine of contempt" circulates, as Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of the Canadian Parliament, expresses it.
This constant portrayal of a nation as the enemy of humanity is in reality a campaign against the Jewish people.
So lie the numerous anti-Jewish attacks in many countries at the depictions of Israel that employ antisemitic terminology.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this slanderous language in connection with the Middle East.
In comparison to earlier outbreaks of anti-Semitism, today's antisemitism is less about attacks on individual Jews, but more about an assault on the "collective Jew," that is, against the State of Israel.
Such attacks have set off a chain reaction of assaults on individual Jews and Jewish institutions across Europe and Latin America.
Earlier, the most dangerous antisemites were those who wanted to make the world Judenrein (Jew-free).
The most dangerous antisemites today are those who want to make the world judenstaatrein (Jew-free of the state).
